description.p:
The method of the invention specifically covers the following:
(1) To provide a warning to a user when the safety margin time is infringed upon;
(2) Optionally, if selected by the user, to perform an automatic grading margin increment based on the warnings raised to restore the correct grading margin at the relay;
(3) To store a record in the upstream relay based on the alarm warning, such that post-fault analysis can determine the source of the problem.

Other characteristics and advantages of the figure will become clearer upon reading preferred embodiments of the invention made in reference to the attached figures among which:
Figure 1 shows a simplistic system topology showing the concept of upstream and downstream IEDs;
Figure 2 shows curves illustrating the time-current characteristics of the upstream and downstream IEDs shown in figure 1;
Figures 3A-3G are time diagrams to explain the working of the invention in relation with the system of figure 1.

The invention discussed in this patent makes use of the time-current characteristics of the over current function. Figure 3A-3G are time diagrams allowing explanation of the working of the invention in relation with the system of figure 1:
Figure 3A shows a time line which corresponds to the successive events which happen;
Figure 3B shows the current I(IEDB) seen by the Intelligent Electronic Device IEDB;
Figure 3C shows the timer command TC(IEDB) of the Intelligent Electronic Device IEDB;
Figure 3D shows the trip control TRC(IEDB) of the Intelligent Electronic Device IEDB;
Figure 3E shows the current I(IEDA) seen by the Intelligent Electronic Device IEDA;
Figure 3F shows the timer command TE(IEDA) of the Intelligent Electronic Device IEDA;
Figure 3G shows the trip control TRC(IEDA) of the Intelligent Electronic Device IEDA.

The technique used in the present patent is that:
(1) At the instant when the current is removed the technique calculates the fractional counter position (i.e. what fraction of the counter's ultimate target the element has progressed towards tripping);
(2) At the same time the maximum current recorded prior to the instant of reset is also recorded;
Using above (1) and (2), the technique calculates the time left to trip, had the current not been removed by downstream fault clearance;
(3) In the event the time left to trip has infringed into the alarm time (a fast and accurate pre-trip alarm timer is a pre-requisite of this invention) the technique will raise an alarm.
